In sum, the way in which the literature assesses the role of political contestation and sunk costs on vote buying leaves many unaddressed gaps. First, part of the literature seems to suggest that clientelist political parties waste valuable resources when buying votes in uncontested elections. Second, part of the literature explains higher levels of clientelist spending by focusing only on current available resources while overlooking the role of prior losses or investments on vote buying (i.e., sunk costs). We interpret this apparent ``misbehavior'' \parencite{Thaler:2015vy} as an analytical problem, particularly, a misunderstanding of how political parties make decisions under risk. To bridge these gaps, the next section introduces prospect theory \parencite{Kahneman1979} to the study of vote buying. Importantly, next section sheds light on why parties buy votes when they are winning the election and why sunk costs might explain massive spendings on vote buying.

\section{Prospect Theory and Its Implications for Clientelism: When Losses Loom Larger than Gains}

% the best theory was developed
Prospect theory is a theory of decision making under conditions of risk \parencite[15]{McDermott1998}, and it was developed by \textcite{Kahneman1979} as a way to incorporate empirically observed violations of expected utility (\cite[179]{Levy1992a}, \cite[290]{McDermott2004}). Since its development, prospect theory has emerged as a ``leading alternative'' \parencite[171]{Levy1992a}, ``best available description,'' \parencite[173]{Barberis2013} and ``empirically correct theory'' \parencite[334]{Vis2011} about how people evaluate risk \parencite[5]{Ackert2006}, particularly excelling in providing a model that offers ``descriptively accurate formulations'' of the human decision-making process \parencite[292]{McDermott2004}.\footnote{\emph{Descriptive} analyses focus on decision-making processes ``as they are,'' in sharp contrast to \emph{normative} analyses, where the focus is on ``how they should be'' (\cite[341]{Kahneman1984a}, see also \cite{Thaler1980a}).} Importantly, it should be noted that while attitudes toward risk are usually portrayed as aspects of personality \parencite[1406]{March1987}, prospect theory is \emph{not} a personality theory; that is, it is not necessary to know about the individual personality traits of decision-makers in order to predict behavior (\cite[293]{McDermott2004}, \cite[335]{Vis2011})


% influence of the theory--where else this theory has been applied.
While the theory has been most influential among international relations scholars, it has unfortunately had ``limited'' influence on political science as a whole \parencite[2]{Mercer2005}. Still, there are several contributions in comparative politics that take prospect theory as a framework. For instance, \textcite{Weyland2002} studies levels of loss aversion of dictatorships when they perform radical economic reforms. \textcite{Vis2009,Vis:2010tq} study welfare state reform showing that political gains are the necessary condition for not-unpopular reforms, while deteriorating socio-economic situations or political losses are necessary for unpopular reforms. Additionally, \textcite{Steinacker2006} studies issue salience, \textcite{Schumacher2015a} focuses on party platform change, and \textcite{Carreras2019} argues that ``citizens who were in the domain of economic losses were more likely to take a risk and vote in favor of Brexit.''


% main principles and contrasts with EUT
Since others have already provided very comprehensive overviews of prospect theory \parencite{Levy1992a,Levy1992,Levy1997,McDermott1998,McDermott2004,Mercer2005,Vis2011,Barberis2013,Linde2017,Vieider2019}, we will limit this section to describing its main components.\footnote{For the purposes of this paper, we will focus on the main implications of the value function, leaving other aspects of the theory, such as the probability weighting function \parencite[220-221]{Levy2003a} for future research.} The theory is based on two empirically derived concepts \parencite[334]{Vieider2019}. First, utilities are defined over changes in outcomes with respect to a reference point (``reference dependence''). Note the sharp contrast with expected value theories, where the focus is on absolute levels of wealth \parencite[5-6]{Ackert2006}. Second, individuals distort values of outcomes in an asymmetrical, non-linear, S-shaped way when making risky decisions (``value-function dependence''). Note also another important difference with expected value theories, where agents are assumed to treat expected utility values linearly, something that does not seem to go away, ``even with training and effort'' \parencite[293]{McDermott2004}.\footnote{Note that expected utility theory essentially assumes a non-linear utility function for risk averse and risk acceptant (but not risk averse) actors. I thank one of the reviewers for this comment.} As \textcite[18]{McDermott1998} clearly summarize it, ``prospect theory predicts that individuals tend to be risk averse in a domain of gains, and relatively risk seeking in a domain of losses.'' This distinction also separates prospect theory from expected value theory, where the latter assume that whether decision-makers are in a domain of gain or loss should not affect their attitude toward risk \parencite[1]{Mercer2005}.


% central idea in prospect theory (Reference dependence)
Reference dependence is the central idea in prospect theory (\cite[40]{McDermott1998}, \cite[178]{Barberis2013}). This aspect of the theory allows people's preferences to depend on the circumstances they face (\cite[1412]{March1987}, \cite[293-294]{McDermott2004}, \cite[168]{Fatas2007}), which is usually \parencite[335]{Vis2011}, but not always \parencite[174]{Levy1992a}, the \emph{status quo},\footnote{The location of the reference point emerges as a critical factor in the analysis of decisions \parencite[288]{Kahneman1979}. \textcite[174]{Levy1992a} explains that the reference point could also be an ``aspiration level.'' In a similar way, \textcite[1135]{Koszegi2006} developed the idea of a reference point that consists of  ``expectations rather than the status quo.'' We owe this point to Salomo Hirvonen.} and how it shifts over time (\cite[28]{McDermott1998}, \cite[301]{McDermott2004}).\footnote{While we do not focus on the role of emotions, others have found that ``sad people will take more risk when trying to avoid a certain loss'' \parencite[6]{Campos-Vazquez2014}.} As \textcite[273]{Kahneman1979} put it more clearly, ``the carriers of value or utility are changes of wealth, rather than final asset positions.'' An important consequence is that, contrary to the assumption of invariance \parencite[186]{Barberis2013}, a shift in the reference point should also lead to reversals of preferences (\cite[719]{Quattrone1988}, \cite[643]{Thaler1990}, \cite[218]{Levy2003a}). %For instance, there is strong support for the idea that prior losses or ``sunk costs'' influence decisions, contrary to what normative theorists propose (\cite[643]{Thaler1990}, \cite[218]{Levy2003a}). 



% central idea in prospect theory (value-function dependence), % value-function dependence explained
Value-function dependence is another central idea in prospect theory. Importantly, the shape of the value function is non-linear. In the domain of gains, the concavity of the value function encourages risk aversion, while in the domain of losses, the convexity of the value function encourages risk-seeking behaviors \parencite[183-184]{Levy1992a}. Formally, the asymmetrical curvature of the value function explains why individuals exhibit risk-averse behaviors in choices among gains but risk-acceptant behaviors in choices among losses \parencite[87]{Levy1997}. A direct consequence of this is that prospect theory pays considerable attention to losses.\footnote{Losses have also been the focus in other areas of political science \parencite[298]{McDermott2004}. For instance, \textcite[132]{Lau1985} explains that ``negative information is more influential than comparable positive information.''} In fact, \textcite[171]{Levy1992a} explains that individuals ``give more weight to losses than to comparable gains,'' which translates into the famous statement \emph{losses loom larger than gains}. From an analytical point of view, we consider this to be \emph{the} feature that trumps the normative expectations contained in standard expected-value theories. 

% Unlike theories based on expected-value calculations, \textcite{Kahneman:2012tc} explains that the process of underweighting of likely events contributes to risk aversion, while very unlikely events are overweighted ``quite grossly or neglected altogether'' (see also \cite[32]{McDermott1998}). % \textcite[32]{McDermott1998} explains that ``prospect theory accounts for these discrepancies by noting the extreme (over)weight and attention that individuals give to small probabilities.'' 



% In prospect theory, both reference dependence and the shape of the value function lead to a more accurate description of decision-making under risk. 
% In particular, the evidence suggests that in the domain of losses, risk-seeking decision-makers take disproportionate risks to avoid certain losses \parencite[297, 299-300]{Levy1992}, 


% In fact, experimental evidence consistently finds evidence of decision-makers distorting values of outcomes in a non-linear way \parencite[87]{Levy1997}

% This is explained because decision-makers ``have difficulty with probability at extreme ranges'' \parencite[30]{McDermott1998}
 
% implications for vote buying
The implications for vote buying are considerable. In sharp contrast to traditional vote-buying theories, prospect theory predicts that clientelist parties will likely buy votes when they are winning the election, that is, when they are in the domain of gains. In these scenarios, parties will find intolerable the idea of potentially losing the supporter base they already have, particularly because decision-makers are more concerned with \emph{preventing} a decline than increasing gains \parencite[89]{Levy1997}. Analytically, under such circumstances of ``loss aversion'' \parencite{Kahneman1984a,Kahneman1991a,Levy1992a,McDermott2004,Mercer2005}---i.e., parties giving more weight to potential losses---the value function will encourage risk-averse behaviors, making investments in vote buying more attractive. Our argument is consistent with \parencite[297, 299-300]{Levy1992} who explains that in the domain of gains, risk-averse decision-makers are excessively eager to secure gains, and with \textcite[1042]{Schumacher2015a}, who find that ``loss aversion motivates [agents] to become risk acceptant.''


Importantly, it should be noted that the aversion is with respect to potential negative electoral outcomes (i.e., losing an already acquired supporter base). This is consistent with prospect theory, particularly, with the concept of ``endowment effect:'' the very process of acquiring something (e.g. a supporter base) enhances the value of the object \parencite{Thaler1980a,Kahneman1990a}. In these situations, decision-makers (parties) should tend to over-value current possessions \parencite[175]{Levy1992a}, making the risky strategy (vote buying) seem more attractive. In fact, \textcite{Horowitz2002} find that losing something looms 2.5 times more than obtaining it, thus making agents more eager to hold on to the good.  

% Hence, we expect vote buying to be higher in contexts where parties are winning the election.

% summary
In addition, our argument complements with other empirical studies that confirm that ``actors perceive themselves to be in the domain of losses more often than we would normally expect,'' even if they are not (\cite[291]{Levy1992}; see also \cite{Lau1985}). Thus, the empirical consequences of both loss aversion and endowment effect combined with the perception of enhanced losses will push winning parties to be more prone to gamble more resources on vote buying. Analytically, the idea of potentially losing something (voters) will shift the decision-maker's (party) reference point, driving them to take the risky alternative (vote buying). %Decision-makers in those situations will generally find intolerable the idea of losing acquired assets---this also applies even to ``trivial [ones, such] as candy bars or coffee mugs'' \parencite[175]{Levy1992a}.



% an enhanced // enhancing then the false perception that agents might actually be in the domain of losses. 

% 2 why Clientelist parties should buy votes when they have experienced important losses or spendings in the past
Moving forward, clientelist parties can also be expected to buy more votes when they are in the domain of losses because of risk-seeking. In these cases, vote buying should be higher when they have experienced important losses or when they have had high spending levels in the past. In line with prospect theory, we argue that past losses are harder to accept, and hence when things have been bad in the past, decision-makers are more likely to make risky choices ``today'' to recover ``yesterday's'' losses \parencite[294]{McDermott2004}. Analytically, \textcite[297]{Levy1992} notes that the elasticity of the risk-seeking behavior is quite high because the magnitudes of past losses need not be large in order to induce the behavior. This means that even small losses can be expected to induce risk-seeking behaviors. %Consequently, we expect a steeper predicted effect in the data analyses. 


Importantly, the risk-seeking behavior is with respect to vote buying as a strategy. By shifting the decision-makers' reference point downward, vote buying seems more attractive because of the tendency of individuals in the domain of losses to try to ``break-even''  \parencite{Thaler1990}. Unlike traditional understandings of the ``incumbency advantage,'' our argument implies that clientelist political parties should be expected to buy more votes not necessarily because they want to win the next election but because they will try to compensate for past losses or ``sunk costs.''\footnote{Due to the ``cost of governing'' \parencite{Powell1993,Nannestad2002,Bawn2012}, \textcite[1041]{Schumacher2015a} empirically find that incumbents in the domain of losses take more risks. In terms of our argument, we also find it plausible for incumbents to fear losing office, thus incentivizing investments in clientelism. However, while our explanation complements theirs, our experimental design and the data analyses focus on incumbency and sunk costs. Building on \textcite{Schumacher2015a}, we encourage future experimental research to problematize the incumbent's risk of losing office. We owe this point to one of the reviewers.} Hence, we expect that clientelist parties will buy more votes when their past electoral losses or past levels of clientelist investments have been high. Clientelist parties that have a history of lost elections or that have invested considerable amounts in vote buying in the past are possible examples of this mechanism. 



