\section{Experimental Design: Buying Votes in the Lab}

% formal model
%Formal models can help experimentalists to determine which theoretical settings and equilibria are most relevant to a particular causal hypothesis (\cite{McDermott2002}, \cite{Aldrich2011} and \cite[174]{Barberis2013}). Thus, in \autoref{formal:model} we developed a vote-buying game within the Downsian paradigm \parencite{Downs:1957vg,Enelow:1990aa}. The idea was to test the descriptive accuracy of the game-theory model in an experimental context (\cite[559]{Bassi2011}, \cite{Dickson2011}, \cite{Aldrich2012}, \cite[361]{Tyszler2016}, \cite[1]{Vieider2019}). 

We designed an economic experiment based on traditional theories of voting and vote buying. This feature is particularly relevant for our identification strategy because most traditional or ``spatial'' theories of vote buying are based on expected utility assumptions. This section empirically tests those assumptions. Epistemologically, an experiment based on classic economic maximization becomes a ``crucial case'' if the goal is to test hypotheses in the context of prospect theory. Thus, the ``least-likely'' design approach presented in this paper should improve the inferential leverage of our results \parencite[12]{Levy2008}.% As \parencite[12]{Levy2008} explains, ``[i]nferential leverage from a least likely case is enhanced if our theoretical priors for the leading alternative explanation make it a most likely case for that theory.''


%The model tried to account for several alternative causal explanations of vote buying. While there are a number of important issues that have been studied, the model paid attention to three of what we consider are the main ones. 

% role
%Building on the formal model, we designed a lab economic experiment. 
As \autoref{experimental:design:fig} shows, at the beginning of every game, participants received a role at random. Following \textcite{Dickson2011}, roles were presented using neutral terminology to maximize experimental control. The design incorporated the following roles: \emph{party A}, \emph{party B}, or \emph{voter}. Every game was played among three players (one \emph{party A}, one \emph{party B}, and one \emph{voter}).

