% vote share
Moving forward, both parties received at random an initial vote share, that is, a \emph{certain} number of (fictional) voters that were going to cast their votes for each party. Overall, this experimental condition mimics the degree to which an election is contested. This portion of the design accomplishes two goals. First, it puts parties in different environments of electoral contestation. In other words, it introduces the element of risk (of losing the election) in the game. Since voters win or lose points when their parties win or lose elections, this risk is also relevant for players acting the ``voter'' role. Second, it gives (or not) voters a certain amount of electoral leverage. Since \textcite{Downs:1957vg}, traditional spatial theories of voting have considered that pivotal voters have more weight in an election. For instance, votes have more value in close electoral races. Thus, given that their votes are more decisive, they might have incentives to sell them at higher prices. It is key in our experimental design that all these pieces of information are public.

% pivotal
%Third, it allows to consider whether pivotal voters where targeted by clientelist parties more often than non-pivotal voters. Since \textcite{Downs:1957vg}, traditional spatial theories of voting have considered pivotal voters as more decisive. %Hence, in the model we accounted for such electoral scenarios. All in all, the formal model tries to incorporate these factors that might explain different vote-buying dynamics. 



During the second stage, parties decide whether to buy votes and make an offer to the voter. Experimental subjects acting the ``party'' role that want to buy votes enter a number of points, which ranged from zero to the maximum assigned budget in that round.\footnote{Participants acting the ``party'' role are told that offering a zero amount means that they do not want to buy votes at that time.} The design allows for simultaneous offers (i.e., offers from both parties), one offer, or zero offers. In the third stage, voters evaluate offers (if any). If the party(s) decided that it (they) did not want to make an offer at that time, the voter is told that the party(s) did not make an offer.\footnote{Voters are told that accepting the offer necessarily implies voting for that party. For simplicity, we did not include the possibility of defecting. We discuss the shortcomings of this limitation in the final portion of the paper. We encourage future designs to include this feature.} 




% administrative
Finally, the experiment was conducted in Chile by the \emph{Centre for Experimental Social Sciences (CESS)} administered by the \emph{University of Santiago} and \emph{Oxford University, Nuffield College} between \Sexpr{min(format(as.Date(dat$participant.time_started), format="%B %d %Y"))} and \Sexpr{max(format(as.Date(dat$participant.time_started), format="%B %d %Y"))}. The subject pool were males and females who were at least 18 years old and were recruited in the surroundings of the university district in downtown Santiago. The experiment was programmed in \texttt{O-tree}, the online version of \texttt{Z-tree} \parencite{Fischbacher2007}. At the beginning of each experimental session all participants were required to successfully complete two practice rounds.\footnote{To make sure participants understood the dynamics of the game, they were shown two examples of the voting game. Participants were required to enter the correct number of points each hypothetical participant would have received in each example. Importantly, all actual participants had to enter the exact number of points to continue playing the game.} Those data were not used in the statistical analyses. In addition, subjects received a show-up payment of \$2,000 CLP ($\approx$ \texteuro2.1). Following \textcite{Harrison2006} and others, our experimental design minimizes hypothetical bias and ``cheap talk'' by compensating subjects with real money according to the quality of their decisions \parencite{Morton:2010ly,Dickson2011}.\footnote{\textcite[95]{Levy1997} notes that in poorer societies (like the Chilean society), conducting research with relatively smaller monetary incentives is still meaningful. However, see \textcite{Morton:2010ly,Bassi2011}.} \autoref{payoffs:plot:fig} shows the density of payoffs expressed in actual currency, by role. A total of \Sexpr{as.numeric(length(unique(v.buying.dat$participant.code)))} subjects were recruited. Each subject played the game three times. The total sample size is \Sexpr{as.numeric(nrow(dat.v.b))}. \autoref{summary:stats:t} shows summary statistics broken down by individual pre-treatment observables. These covariates were captured by a battery of socio-demographic questions delivered at the end of the study.\footnote{The table also details the same information conveyed in \autoref{payoffs:plot:fig}.} For every new game, a whole new randomization process took place.\footnote{That is, participants received a role, an ``ideology,'' a party endowment and a contestability structure.} Formally, we follow an in-between-subjects design, where different groups of individuals are randomly assigned to various experimental or control conditions \parencite{McDermott2002,Tyszler2016,Hwang2021}.


% experimental points
All transactions were performed exchanging experimental ``points.'' Again, we endeavored to employ neutral terminology to maximize experimental control \parencite{Dickson2011}. Thus, throughout all three games, participants bought and sold votes (if any) and accumulated and lost wealth expressed purely in experimental points. Every experimental point was equivalent to \$\Sexpr{as.numeric(unique(dat$session.config.real_world_currency_per_point))} CLP ($\approx$ \texteuro0.00045). Participants learned about the conversion when reading the initial instructions. Final payoffs were converted to actual currency at the end of the study.

% external validity
Finally, from an external validity standpoint, we believe that voters in real elections can estimate, with some degree of success, actual vote shares (for instance, by looking at electoral polls). Voters can also identify parties' ideological positions. For example, \textcite{Luna2005} identify a number of conditions that are associated with higher levels of elite-mass congruence in Latin America.\footnote{However, see \textcite{Visconti2021}.} Voters can also make inferences about a party's endowment, and how those endowments can be redistributed in a clientelist fashion \parencite{Auyero2000}. In turn, the literature is consistent in that brokers also provide necessary information about available resources and how to gain access to them \parencite{Murillo2021a}. %In sum, we believe our design appropriately captures the decision-making process of political parties under risk.



\section{Statistical Analyses: Vote Buying and Risk}


% internal validity
Since the focus of this paper is on vote buying, we discarded the voter data and analyzed all observations $i$ acting any of the party roles (\emph{party A} and \emph{party B}). In practice, this leaves the data formatted in party-voter dyads. Empirically, we concentrate on one main dependent variable, namely, the amount of the vote-buying offers made by parties (if any). The distribution of this variable is shown in \autoref{dep:var:plot:fig}. 

\begin{figure}[h]
\includegraphics[scale=.6, center]{depvarplot.png}
\caption{{\bf Distribution of the Dependent Variable.\label{dep:var:plot:fig}}}
\caption*{{\bf Note}: Since the focus of this paper is on vote buying, we discarded the voter data. The new sample size consisting only of parties is N = \Sexpr{nrow(m1.d)} (mean = \Sexpr{round(mean(m1.d$offer.made.party),0)}, median = \Sexpr{round(median(m1.d$offer.made.party),0)}).}\centering
